data.name: labelCustomFormatNameID.ToolTip
data.value:
Windows automatically assigns format ID numbers. Names can be assigned to ID numbers by "registering" the name, but not the other way around.
Therefore you can choose a format ID that might already exist, but can't change the name. Or you can choose a custom name and it will be assigned a random format ID.
A format ID of zero is just a placeholder.

data.name: checkBoxPlainTextEditing.ToolTip
data.value:
Be sure to select the correct encoding to edit with.
If you see lots of periods in the text, those are likely null characters that were converted, and you probably therefore want to use UTF-16.
The plaintext will be converted directly back to bytes, so when editing in plaintext, null characters are represented by \0 so that you can use that to signify a null character.
Still, the conversion from plaintext to hex might not be perfect, so if accuracy is important, just edit the hex values directly!

data.name: labelSynthesizedTypeWarn.ToolTip
data.value:
The selected format type is "synthesized", meaning it will be automatically re-created by Windows if deleted (edits should still work).
Synthesized formats are automatically created by Windows if there are certain corresponding formats in the clipboard. For example, if the "CF_TEXT" format exists, Windows will automatically convert it and also add the formats "CF_UNICODETEXT" and "CF_OEMTEXT" if they don't exist already.
Tips: - Windows won't overwrite a synthesized format if it already exists, like you edit it - You can get rid of the synthesized formats by also deleting the other associated formats
